--><ns3676:section xmlns:ns3676="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.processControl.batch">

  <ns3677:title xmlns:ns3677="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Scheduling jobs for idle time via <ns3678:command xmlns:ns3678="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">batch</ns3678:command></ns3677:title>
  <ns3679:para xmlns:ns3679="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    At times you want to schedule jobs to run at times when the system load is below some
    load level. In this case you may want to use <ns3680:command xmlns:ns3680="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">batch</ns3680:command>. It provides 
    the same interface as the <ns3681:command xmlns:ns3681="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">at</ns3681:command> command (see
    <ns3682:xref xmlns:ns3682="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" linkend="resources.information.platforms.linux.processControl.at"/>). Running the
    <ns3683:command xmlns:ns3683="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">batch</ns3683:command> command yields the standard <ns3684:command xmlns:ns3684="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">at</ns3684:command>
    command prompt where you enter the jobs to be run when the system load is low (by
    default less than 0.8, but this can be specified -- see the <ns3685:command xmlns:ns3685="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">man</ns3685:command>
    pages).
  </ns3679:para>
  <ns3686:para xmlns:ns3686="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The time can be specified in the same way as it is done for the <ns3687:command xmlns:ns3687="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">at</ns3687:command>
    command. Scheduling one or more jobs to be batched for some date/time specifies that the
    jobs should be run after that date/time when the system load is sufficiently low.
  </ns3686:para>
</ns3676:section>